rogression and compensation increases. This mechanism supports the plan's adaptability and fairness over time. [Data: Entities (17, 22), Relationships (29, 33, 37, 46, +more)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Termination conditions that end coverage\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Coverage ends under several conditions: ceasing to be an eligible employee, termination of active full-time employment, non-payment of premiums, or termination of the Master Policy by the employer. The latter is particularly impactful, as it ends coverage for all employees regardless of individual compliance. The employee must remain in active full-time employment to maintain coverage, and any change in status triggers the end of benefits. [Data: Entities (26, 27, 28, 25, 24), Relationships (50, 51, 52, 48, 49, +more)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Non-payment of premiums as a barrier to conversion\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Non-payment of premiums is a critical exclusion from the Conversion Privilege. If coverage ends due to non-payment, the employee is not eligible to convert to an Individual Whole Life Policy. This condition ensures that only those who have maintained their coverage through proper premium payments can access the conversion benefit. It reinforces the importance of financial responsibility in preserving long-term insurance options. [Data: Entities (20), Relationships (38, 48, +more)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Maximum Benefit cap ensures plan sustainability\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The Maximum Benefit of $1,000,000 serves as a cap on total coverage, preventing unlimited benefit accumulation. This cap is enforced by the Master Group Policy and applies across both Basic Life and Voluntary Supplemental coverage. It ensures that the plan remains financially sustainable for the employer and insurer while still providing substantial protection for employees. The cap is a structural safegua